segments.text: Anyway, I think we ought to continue talking about your early childhood a little bit more.
I really do.
Again, the things that... Well, you have that and about the Jew peddler coming through.
I have those things, yes.
We've gotten a lot of the isolated things, and I want to run things together now.
Yeah.
Because now's really the time.
I'm going to transcribe verbatim from every take and then cut and paste and put it together.
Yeah, you've got that.
I've got that story.
And you've got the one about carrying the mail across the river horseback.
Got one about the old horse, us feeding her and killing her.
Right.
Now, which one was that?
Oh, Cousy.
Feeding her and killing her?
I don't think we have that.
Yeah.
Yes, you do, too.
I've got that one.
We fed her oats in a tub full of oats.
And me and the little Mexican boy, Jesus, carried the oats in gallon buckets and filled a tub full up and was going to fatten her overnight.
And we did.
She swelled up as big as two horses.
I bet she did.
Yes, she did.
And I know you have that one.
OK.
And I just don't really know.
Well, I'm just thinking, you know, like today you were talking about the values that you feel are missing.
And I guess you feel they're existent in the Texas Hill Country.
Well, they are more so than in a lot of other places in this country.
They are, as far as old talks is concerned.
I think that's important to say.
I mean, you know, you came from a grassroots family.
When you got here, there wasn't much grass yet.
No, I didn't.
I mean, you really... You scrapped a living on a frontier.
As you taught those kids to read today, you told them what a frontier was.
And...
You've never known really any other life as far as your childhood goes.
That's so right.
I've got the stories of Uncle Jesse and things like that.
And you've got the story of Uncle Jesse and Donald's got a wooden leg.
Yeah.
Donald's got a meat skin.
Laid away degrees that mother laid twice a day.
And he'd stomp that wooden leg at me, and man, I'd just cut a beeline out to my mama.
It'd just scare me to death.
You know, it was taken off along about here, and it fastened on.
No, I guess it didn't, because he could bend his knees.
It was all the way under his knee, and it had to come down here.
It had to
a fork like that, and they come together.
And it was just a wooden, he didn't have wooden foot, it was just a wooden stick.
And he'd stomp that thing at me, and man, I would run.
Oh, I bet.
And I know you've got my poem, the first one he ever taught me.
I think I do.
I've got a secret, just be free, Robin and I in the sweet chubby tweed.
But Wobby knows it best.
I believe you've got that one.
I do have that one.
All right.
And then the next one that he taught me, and it's a long one.
The buttercups are coming in the scarlet columbine, and in the sunny meadows the dandelions shine.
Just as many days as your salt cans can hold, the Lord God made them all.
The little bird flew over and oh how sweet they sang to tell the happy children that once again this spring the graving grass comes creeping so soft beneath the feet.
The frogs began to ripple, a music tearing sweet.
Now I learned that before I started school from Uncle Jesse.
What are children missing today?
poetry they're missing the love of poetry and uncle jesse taught me all of that and where did uncle jesse learn this i mean he was a veteran of the civil war uncle jesse uh
Johnson had a good education, and he got it from McGuffey's Readers.
McGuffey's Readers.
That's right.
And he'd get those things out.
Every story in McGuffey's Reader had a moral to it.
It had a principle, and it taught you something.
And he'd sit me down, and he'd say, now you listen.
All right, you saw today with these children that I had in this room, and the last one that came, they do not understand what the word listen means.
And I had to repeat to that little girl three times.
I said, well, honey, how many boxes do you see on that shelf?
One.
Well, what did I tell you?
Get the cookie out of the box.
I said, well, where is the box?
Mm-hmm.
Well, it's here.
I said, now do you know what to do?
Yeah.
She said, get the cookie.
I said, yes.
They never listen.
They do not understand that there is one thing to do but have their eyes glued on that idiot boxer called TV.
That's right.
And there's no morals being taught on television these days.
But there's anything but morals on television.
Exactly right.
I think that's right.
They were missing the boat.
Well, when you grew up, you had literature in your home, as you said.
You also had a mother that wrote songs.
Yes, she did.
She had beautiful songs.
And I hope that we can take some of those and put them into print.
I hope someday that somebody will pick them up.
Well, I know somebody that will pick them up and do an album with them if you're interested.
If they were interested.
Worth it.
They're worth it.
I would love to see them maybe before we go, if we can find them or something like that.
And the thing that most children are missing today is that companionship of older people.
Now, I didn't miss out on a thing in the world for companionship of elderly people because I was the oldest granddaughter in the Johnson family.
in the Bunton family, in the Chapman family, and in the Cox.
See, my grandmother, Chapman, was a Cox before, but no relation to the Cox I married.
And the oldest in the Cox family.
Well, I had all the attention that could be given a little girl.
But for the same token, I had an inferiority complex that wouldn't quit.

very bad why was that um first that's cross-eyed second you know they just didn't wasn't anything or they didn't think could ever be done about it i was about as broad as i was long and i my hair wasn't
Well, it had a wave in it, but my mother plaited it so tight that I couldn't bat my eyes.
And those cross eyes sitting towards Joneses.
And me as fat as a little pig.
And long dresses.
I can see those things, and they just make me so mad because they come to my sheet tops.
Really?
But I had to wear them.
Yeah.
And I had big bows in my hair, and I always had a sash, and I hated those sashes.
We're talking about, because you were born in 1905, right?
And so here in Texas in 1905, you were wearing your long dresses, you were wearing your pigtails, and you were living without the...
The fancy city life that everybody else in the country was trying to aspire to have.
That's right.
I can remember just as well as it is yesterday when I had my first pair of patent leather slippers.
Yeah.
I was seven years old, and I just thought I was uptown.
Right.
And I was.
Sure.
And they were called Mary Janes.
Really?
Put out by Buster Brown.
Oh, yes.
Good old Buster Brown.
Buster Brown shoes.
And then the next pair of pretty shoes that I had, I bought from a Jew store here in Johnson City, and his name was Max Mellinger.
Max Mellinger.
Uh-huh.
And they were really pretty.
Uh-huh.
They were black patent leather, and they had red kid's skin tops laced up.
Oh, my, were they ever pretty.
And I had, well, we called it a bearskin coat, but it wasn't.
It was an imitation fur, and it was red.
Uh-huh.
And by then, I'd had my eyes straightened.
Uh-huh.
And I'd kind of trimmed up.
And that was seven, about seven?
I guess I must have been, oh, I had my eyes straightened when I was 10.
So I was about 10 years old.
And I had slammed down to where I was at least I could get through the door.
And at school, they'd call me Donna because that's fat and all that kind of stuff.
But anyway, I was so proud of that little red-skinned,
Bare skin coat.
Oh, I was so proud.
Well, we'd had one once before, but it was a chinchilla effect that we'd bought from a peddler and it came through.
But this one was bought from Max Mellinger here.
And it's right where, his store is right where the old theater is now.
Oh.
That's right.
And it was really a nice store.
And he had nice goods.
And he was well thought of in the community and...
Was your grandfather, was he here after your grandfather or before?
After my grandfather came here.
Oh, okay.
They were good friends.
They were.
I thought they might be.
Yeah, they were.
That is natural.
Yes, I know.
I'll tell you, you can't, you might separate them, but you can't, you might separate them in distance.
But not, they'll find each other.
They do.
I know.
Not only in that way, but financially in every other way, if it's needed.
Right, that's true.
If it's needed, that's part of their living, that's part of their life, that's part of their bringing up.
Tradition, right.
You bet it is.
You said you didn't find out that your grandfather was Jewish until you were a grown woman.
A grown woman, right, okay.
And you didn't really know what that was about at all, did you?
No, I didn't even know.
But I knew why, that he would tell me about this compulsory military training.
In Europe, right, in Germany?
In Germany, and why he didn't want it.
And he also told me when I was a girl, well, it was before World War I,
He said, the one we had better be watching out for is Japan.
He'd never say Japan.
He'd always say Japan.
He says, they're going to sneak around.
They're sneakers.
They're going to get you.
And they're going to find us asleep.
And they're going to hurt us.
And he saw a war pending?
Yes, he did.
And he kept telling us that.
While I was in high school,
And I thought, well, Grandpa just has the awfulest feeling.
I wonder why.
And he came back and he said, I'll tell you something else.
He said, well, my daddy was called up for World War I.
But peace was signed before he had to go.
But anyway, he was called up into the service.
And so was Kitty Clyde's father, all of them.
And my grandfather told them, he says, you may whip the Germans down, but they'll come back.
You may think you've got them whipped, but they'll come back.
And when they do, they will be against you.
You're going to feed them, you're going to clothe them, and you're going to help them everywhere in the world to establish their government.
And they're going to turn on you, and when they do,
It's going to hurt you.
Really?
So it's sort of a folk wisdom of world politics that you grew up with.
That I actually grew up with and had no newspapers, no nothing.
My grandfather was a well-read man and a man of few words in public.
My grandmother talked for the family.
But my grandfather had very little to say.
And where did his grandmother, I know that's his second wife, because his first wife died?
No, his mother died.
It was his mother that died.
Mother that died, yeah.
And he took this, he was a twin.
And he and his twin sister, and her name was Clyde.
That's where my mother got the name of Kitty Clyde.
And he took this, well, yeah.
They landed at Indiola and came on over to Houston.
And my grandfather came from Houston to Brenham.
And there was a German settlement that stopped in there, a bunch of the German immigrants that stopped in there.
And my grandfather got a job working on the first railroad dump that was built from Brenham to Houston.
Really?
Now that, to me, is something.
I look back and I say, yes.
You know, I told you the night before last, I said, you can't find half a dozen Jews in the world that were pioneers, that would brave the wilderness first.
They waited until it was settled, and then they came.
My grandfather braved the wilderness.
He did.
Yeah, he did.
He definitely did.
Yeah.
And then came...
Well, anyway, grandmother died, and Aunt Beth and Uncle Alex was younger than Clyde and Jim.
Jim was grandfather.
James Henry was his name.
Mm-hmm.
they were younger than James and Henry and Clyde.
But they made a home for these children.
And grandfather married again.
Your great-grandfather.
My great-grandfather married again.
But he changed his name from Chapman, S-H, or?
S-H-A-P-M-A-W-N, C-H-A-P-M-A-N. Chapman.
Chapman.
He changed Chapman to Chapman.
So he changed it.
And he was afraid that he'd be tracked down, sent back, and put to work.
Because he was so tall and so big for his age.
And he was a grown man at 13.
And naturally, he was scared to death.
He was running scared.
But then they moved to Round Rock.
The entire family.
Yeah.
Moved over to Round Rock.
And then grandfather met grandmother.
This was in the 1800s.
Yes.
About 1854.
Well, grandfather came here before then.
Let's see.
Grandmother and grandfather.
Let's see.
Grandfather came here about 18 and got here in time for the Civil War.
He was in the Civil War.
I could look it up and I believe it must have been about 1850 because he got here in time to go to the Civil War and he fought in the Civil War.
Grandfather Chapman fought in the Civil War.
Yes, he sure did.
Then he married Grandmother
The same year that Grandpa Johnson married Grandma Bunton.
Oh, really?
That's like 1878.
And then, I believe that's Kitty Clyde coming now.
Oh, all right.
Looks like somebody.
Damn, I have no time.
Excuse me.
Uh-huh.
But that's who it is.
Okay.
Mm-hmm.
They married.
Chapman.
Chapman.
And Uncle Buddy was born in 1880.
That's right.
Mm-hmm.
Okay.
And Aunt Mabel was born in 1882, and my mother was born in 1885.
Okay.
Right down that line.
Sure.
I'll have to see what she says.
For sure.
Well, I'll cut this off for a second.
When he was president of the Republic of Texas, and he was offered the gift of the teletype to Texas.
And for two years, Houston didn't answer.
Houston didn't recognize it.
So he sits down and he writes him a letter, and he says, I take that you don't care for my offer, and so I am withdrawing it.
Well, had he taken that offer today, we would not be burdened with taxes, but we would be living off of the revenue that that... Of the telegraph.
Of the telegraph that would be...
brought in to Texas.
They wanted to try it here?
Is that what it was?
They wanted to set up a system?
To give it to Texas alone, the man alone, willed it to Texas.
As a republic?
Yes.
Isn't that something?
That is very true.
That's amazing.
That's another thing about you I've got to say.
Because of when you were born and because of who your relatives were, whereas we talk about seeing so-and-so here or meeting this dignitary there,
Your life, the way of your life, was what history was at that time and who these people were.
And there just were not that many people in Texas as you realized when your grandparents were here that everybody was involved.
That's right.
In the building of this day.
That's very true.
And it's firsthand.
It's firsthand.
And right there, oh.
Grandpa Baines borrowed money from Sam Houston.
Uh-huh.
And the letter is down there in the library.
Uh-huh.
Stating, thank you for loaning me the $150 that I am returning.
Uh-huh.
When you say there was a close bill of relation, there was.
Yes.
Well, all right.
When I was a little girl...
down here on the ranch, and we were driving.
We sold our steers to Tom Stribling.
And we had to take them to Marble Falls.
That was the closest railroad.
Well, you don't cross steers over a Colorado River.
Now, that's for sure.
Not then.
All right.
And we took them on over to Fairland to put them in on the train to take them across.
We came back.
And we stayed all night at Grandma Stribling's house over here at Round Mountain.
Now that's horseback riding.
That's not trailer horse business like these trail rides they have today.
But that was sitting in the saddle all day long and come back that far.
And we went to... And that's driving how many head of cattle?
Well, altogether, we had 200 and I believe it was 275.
Well, we're supposed to have had 290, but we lost that many in the...

cedar brakes from here there now that's no joke oh sure and so that's then when we got them on then we had to come back well we went through these pastures and that's the reason every one of us had to know every earmark and cattle brand in this country and it was just as automatic as
Yes, it was a way of life.
And we knew what that was branded.
We knew what the earmark was.
And we knew whether it belonged in our herd or not.
Like license plates from different states.
Absolutely.
It's exactly like license plates from different states.
But you knew it.
Yeah.
And you would know whether it belonged in your herd or not.
Right.
So we brought these.
Well, we didn't get them all.
I'll never forget that.
Tom liked that a fit.
But we didn't get them all.
We didn't get but 15.
Where the other four got to, I...
I don't know, but we brought back 15 and they went in the next shipment.
But grandma, scribbling that night, told us that we could sleep on the porch and on our saddle blanket and use our saddle for a pillow.
I never will forget that.
I'd never done anything like that, but I did it.
I learned.
That you could.
Didn't smell very good, that saddle blanket.
But it was all right.
I bet it didn't.
But before we went to bed, we asked her what she did when she was a little girl.
Because she was from East Texas.
She told us about going to Sunday school in a surrey.
And we knew what a Surrey was, because Grandpa Johnson had one.
And he'd take us to church in it.
She said, Sam Houston and I would ride to Sunday School, Baptist Sunday School, in the same Surrey every Sunday.
So I knew who Sam Houston was as a little girl.
A little girl.
I wasn't over 10 years old, but I knew the history of Sam Houston from...
Way back.
From hearsay firsthand?
Yeah, hearsay firsthand.
And she told us what kind of a fellow he was.
And she told us he didn't have much money.
And as I read on in history and I found out, by the way, he didn't have enough to pay his announcing fee.
Yeah.
That's right.
So it was paid for him.
Well, that's no disgrace, but...
There's been lots of poor people who made it good in history that came out wealthy, but there's no disgrace in being poor.
But there's a disgrace in being ornery with it.
That's what makes you a disgraceful person, being ornery by being poor and unclean.
How poor you can be, you can still be clean.
You can still think good.
You can still have good principles.
You can still be a man or a woman and look the whole world in the face.
It's not where you live, it's how you live.
It's how you meet your fellow man.
It's lots of times, it's the kind word that you didn't say that day.
Or it may be...
The handshake that you wish you had grabbed and said, old boy, you did a good job.
Or the pat on the back for the little one that fell aside on the race.
You've run a good race, fella.
You did your best.
You didn't do it.
It's the smile that the cripple might have needed who was sitting on the side of the road.
waiting just a hand.
But you didn't have time to stop and say, I'll help you.
Maybe it was an old woman at the crossing of the street.
Her feet were feeble.
She's slow.
Her eyesight was bad.
But you were in a hurry.
You didn't have time.
Life meant nothing.
But hurry, hurry, hurry.
But to her, it may have been her last step had it been wrong.
But you didn't have time.
All of those things add up at the setting of the sun.
It gives you a bit of heartache that you can never overcome.
You just can't do it because that day is gone.
It's gone.
You can't recall it.
It may never come your way again to have a chance to be kind.
I'd rather be...
Do you think these values are the values behind the people here in Johnson City?
I do.
I believe it's stronger than anything.
As I have said a hundred times, and I'll say it again, this is a hard land to make a living in.
You have to dig deeper.
In other words, the worm is there,
Mr. Rooster, but you've got to scratch deeper.
So with people here, we know that we have to work harder to produce whatever we have.
And I have often said that the oak tree in this country is typical of the people who live here.

Because you can look at it, and it's bent from the snarls of the hard, cold winters, the dry summers, the hard hails, the winds, and the hardships that has hit it and bent it in different forms and fashions.
Yet, you look at it, its roots are deep
They're big, and they are grown out and out, and the limbs spread out and out, and they touch each way in the north, east, and south.
That's exactly the way the people are in Blanco County, in Gillespie County.
Their hands are outstretched to one another, and they help you when you need it.
But you prove yourself first that you're worthy of that help.
You find no soup lines here.
You find no beggars on the street.
They believe in an honest day's work for an honest dollar.
And that's been our way of life.
And our children are missing that value.
Our children are, oh, I hope you don't have to work as hard as I did.
I don't believe in that stuff.
I think they should know that it doesn't hurt to pull a cotton sack and have a bullnettle whip you on your little bare legs and how they hurt and how hot it is.
That's true.

and boll weevil stung cotton and you'll pick them you'll go home and your blood will be dripping off of the end of your fingers from where the burrs have stuck it all day it wouldn't hurt these girls or boys to have a taste of that it wouldn't hurt them to have a taste of sitting in the saddle all day long and having a well we called it dried beef they call it jerky now but
We'd take a hunk of dried beef and a cold biscuit, ride all day long, and eat that cold biscuit and jerky.
Yes, you were tired when you got home.
Your little seat was wore out.
But you still had your night chores to do.
You had a responsibility to do.
I've driven cattle for help for my daddy.
He'd say, well, I have three hands today.
All right.
A dollar a day for my horse and saddle.
And thought I had good money.
I was proud of it.
I could buy school clothes with it.
Life hasn't been easy, but I'm proud of it.
I'm proud.
It has made me a stronger person.
I can look the whole...
